00:07:20.645 --> 00:07:26.485
through Barcelona, or to be precise, Castell de Montjuïc in Barcelona.

00:07:27.425 --> 00:07:31.145
This was the distance that the two men were tasked with measuring.

00:07:32.021 --> 00:07:36.705
But how would this help them come up with the distance for a metre, you might well ask?

00:07:37.449 --> 00:07:42.529
The idea was to use this measurement—from Dunkirk to Barcelona—to

00:07:42.569 --> 00:07:47.219
estimate the total distance from the North Pole to the Equator.

00:07:48.139 --> 00:07:51.679
Astronomers already knew what fraction of that total

00:07:51.679 --> 00:07:55.439
distance the Dunkirk-Barcelona segment represented.

00:07:55.939 --> 00:08:03.629
And by extrapolating this proportion, they could calculate the full pole-to-equator distance.

00:08:04.389 --> 00:08:08.079
They would then divide this distance into 10 million

00:08:08.079 --> 00:08:12.469
units, and each of those units would be called a metre.

00:08:13.649 --> 00:08:20.009
This would mean that the circumference of the Earth would be exactly 40 million metres.

00:08:20.859 --> 00:08:25.449
Remember that, as we’ll address this in more detail a little bit later on.

00:08:26.449 --> 00:08:33.634
Anyway, this might all sound elegant in theory, but this was in 1792.

00:08:34.399 --> 00:08:38.589
How were they actually going to measure the distance between these two points?

00:08:39.079 --> 00:08:43.499
