00:08:44.309 --> 00:08:51.677
Today, we know—thanks to modern satellite technology—that this distance is 1,075 kilometres.

00:08:52.117 --> 00:08:57.327
But Méchain and Delambre had to calculate it from scratch,

00:08:57.707 --> 00:09:02.107
and from that, determine the precise length of a metre.

00:09:03.397 --> 00:09:07.907
As you can probably appreciate, Méchain and Delambre were tasked

00:09:07.917 --> 00:09:11.687
with one of the most challenging surveying operations in history.

00:09:12.867 --> 00:09:20.314
To calculate the distance, they used the method of triangulation, which involves taking angular

00:09:20.314 --> 00:09:27.954
readings from carefully chosen high points—church spires, mountaintops, and miscellaneous tall

00:09:27.954 --> 00:09:36.140
buildings—and then they used geometry to calculate exact distances over large expanses of land.

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:42.260
Essentially, they stood in one high place, observed two points of

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:46.259
interest in the distance, and measured the angles between them.

00:09:47.139 --> 00:09:52.929
But because this was imperfect, they would measure the angles from multiple

00:09:52.949 --> 00:09:58.680
different places, and use all of those calculations to reduce the margin for error.

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:06.910
And they would do this over and over and over, moving all the way from Dunkirk to Barcelona.

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:14.960
Or technically, Delambre did the northern part, from Dunkirk to a town called Rodez in central

00:10:14.970 --> 00:10:21.570
France, and Méchain was responsible for the southern part, from Rodez down to Barcelona.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:28.680
Even though they divided the work, it was incredibly laborious, requiring delicate

00:10:28.710 --> 00:10:34.930
instruments and precise observations, often repeated many times to eliminate errors.

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:42.370
And these instruments were cumbersome: they were heavy brass and steel devices that had

00:10:42.380 --> 00:10:48.800
to be carried up hills, across rivers, and through towns in the midst of political unrest.

00:10:49.670 --> 00:10:54.500
Remember, this was all taking place in the middle of the French Revolution.

