00:13:29.915 --> 00:13:34.115
Meanwhile, Delambre, on his northern journey, was often

00:13:34.115 --> 00:13:38.268
met with confusion or outright hostility from villagers.

00:13:39.485 --> 00:13:46.215
Despite all of this, the pair inched closer to their goal with extraordinary determination.

00:13:47.095 --> 00:13:55.695
By 1798, after almost seven years of gruelling, nerve-wracking work, the two astronomers finally

00:13:55.705 --> 00:14:02.035
had enough data to calculate the length of the meridian arc and, with it, define the metre.

00:14:03.505 --> 00:14:09.879
The calculations were complete, and the true distance of a metre could finally be unveiled.

00:14:10.999 --> 00:14:14.129
For the first time in history, there would be a universal

00:14:14.129 --> 00:14:17.619
measurement based on the circumference of the Earth.

00:14:18.839 --> 00:14:25.863
In 1799, a platinum bar was cast to represent this new standard.

00:14:26.519 --> 00:14:31.459
That bar, known as the “mètre des Archives,” became the reference point for

00:14:31.509 --> 00:14:36.259
all future measurements, and this is where it gets even more interesting.

00:14:37.349 --> 00:14:45.396
Once the metre was set, scientists could define a smaller unit, the decimetre—one-tenth of a metre.

00:14:46.409 --> 00:14:54.260
A cube that measured one decimetre on each side was declared to be one litre in volume.

00:14:54.830 --> 00:14:57.707
Ta-da, a new universal measurement of volume.

00:14:58.587 --> 00:15:03.297
Then, the weight of a litre of water at a specified temperature

00:15:03.817 --> 00:15:08.637
[close to 4°C] was considered to be exactly one kilogramme.

00:15:09.187 --> 00:15:11.997
And ta-da, a new measurement of weight.

00:15:13.187 --> 00:15:22.170
Suddenly, length, volume, and mass were all interlinked, rooted in a single measurement: the metre.

00:15:23.597 --> 00:15:28.367
And because everything was in multiples of ten, conversions

00:15:28.517 --> 00:15:33.167
were vastly simpler than in the old imperial or local systems.

00:15:33.517 --> 00:15:42.157
No more 12 inches in a foot, 3 feet in a yard, 1,760 yards in a mile; now it was

00:15:42.197 --> 00:15:48.957
tens, hundreds, and thousands—a clean, decimal arrangement that anyone but the most

00:15:49.037 --> 00:15:55.097
ardent supporter of pounds, feet and gallons can recognise as a superior system.

00:15:56.507 --> 00:16:02.607
Of course, theory and practice don’t always align immediately, and plenty

00:16:02.607 --> 00:16:07.505
of people in France, especially in rural areas, resisted the new system.

00:16:08.335 --> 00:16:14.955
Napoleon himself, seeing how unpopular it could be, allowed many of the old measures to stay in use.

00:16:15.852 --> 00:16:21.891
But the metric system was already out in the world, and it was only a matter of time

00:16:22.171 --> 00:16:28.191
before its clarity and simplicity caught the attention of scientists in other countries.

00:16:29.301 --> 00:16:33.881
Throughout the 19th century, the idea of a universal, decimal-based

00:16:33.881 --> 00:16:37.441
system of measurement spread across Europe and beyond.

00:16:38.311 --> 00:16:42.261
Newly independent countries in Latin America adopted it as

00:16:42.261 --> 00:16:46.421
a mark of modernity and a break from colonial influences.

00:16:47.411 --> 00:16:52.601
By the late 1800s, the metric system had become a near-global concern,

00:16:53.111 --> 00:16:59.711
and in 1875, seventeen countries signed the Metre Convention, setting

00:16:59.711 --> 00:17:03.561
up the International Bureau of Weights and Measures near Paris.

00:17:04.351 --> 00:17:08.041
Even the United States, which still clings to miles

00:17:08.041 --> 00:17:11.411
and pounds in daily life, was a founding signatory.

00:17:12.862 --> 00:17:17.858
And over the next century, definitions became even more precise.

00:17:18.838 --> 00:17:22.288
Originally, the metre was defined by a platinum

00:17:22.288 --> 00:17:27.538
bar—literally a metal stick kept under lock and key in Paris.

00:17:28.088 --> 00:17:33.298
If anything happened to that bar—if it got a tiny scratch, or if

00:17:33.298 --> 00:17:38.032
the metal warped over time—our definition of the metre would change.

00:17:38.722 --> 00:17:44.162
Scientists realised that basing the metre on a single physical object wasn’t

00:17:44.192 --> 00:17:50.772
ideal, so in 1983, they redefined the metre using the speed of light in

00:17:50.772 --> 00:17:54.892
a vacuum, which is one of the most reliable properties in the universe.

00:17:55.802 --> 00:18:07.152
We say that the metre is the distance light travels in 1/299,792,458 of a second.

00:18:08.502 --> 00:18:12.232
Because the speed of light doesn’t change, we get an incredibly

00:18:12.252 --> 00:18:17.012
precise, unchanging definition of what a metre actually is.

00:18:18.052 --> 00:18:21.302
And a similar logic applies to the kilogramme.

00:18:22.282 --> 00:18:29.162
For a long time, the official kilogramme was a platinum-iridium cylinder, also kept in Paris.

00:18:30.202 --> 00:18:35.702
Just like the metre bar, any tiny imperfection or contamination

00:18:36.032 --> 00:18:40.572
could change its mass, even if only by an infinitesimal amount.

00:18:41.612 --> 00:18:48.152
So, in 2019, scientists decided to define the kilogramme in terms

00:18:48.172 --> 00:18:52.589
of Planck's constant, a fundamental number in quantum physics.

00:18:53.769 --> 00:19:00.181
If we measure Planck's constant accurately and link it to the idea of mass, we get a

00:19:00.181 --> 00:19:05.611
definition of the kilogramme that doesn’t rely on a single metal cylinder sitting in a vault.

00:19:06.271 --> 00:19:13.201
It’s tied, instead, to a property of the universe that remains the same no matter where you go.

00:19:14.141 --> 00:19:19.261
This can all be traced back to Méchain and Delambre’s incredible precision.

00:19:20.021 --> 00:19:25.291
But, and it is a big but, they did make a tiny mistake.

00:19:26.461 --> 00:19:31.921
As you’ll remember, they had intended the distance from the North Pole to the equator to be

00:19:31.961 --> 00:19:40.301
exactly ten million metres, making the Earth’s polar circumference exactly 40 million metres.

00:19:41.391 --> 00:19:44.791
That figure was close, but not exact.

00:19:45.941 --> 00:19:52.351
Thanks to a series of tiny errors—some the result of the Earth’s irregular shape, others

00:19:52.361 --> 00:19:58.831
from errors in the triangulation work—the final calculation was off by a few hundred metres.

00:20:00.261 --> 00:20:07.309
And if you trace the sources of this discrepancy, most fingers point to Pierre Méchain.

00:20:08.242 --> 00:20:14.132
He was an obsessively meticulous man who discovered inconsistencies in his results but

00:20:14.492 --> 00:20:20.142
never fully corrected them, partly out of fear of undermining the entire endeavour.

00:20:21.522 --> 00:20:27.132
As more precise measurements emerged in the decades and centuries that followed, scientists

00:20:27.132 --> 00:20:33.402
realised that the meridian distance should have been slightly larger, meaning our

00:20:33.402 --> 00:20:40.612
metre–the metre that you and I know–turned out to be just a fraction smaller than intended.

00:20:41.962 --> 00:20:44.772
But by then, it was too late.

00:20:45.402 --> 00:20:49.642
The metre had already become the reference for countless measurements,

00:20:49.932 --> 00:20:55.242
scientific instruments, legal contracts, textbooks, and everyday transactions.

00:20:56.072 --> 00:21:01.362
There were discussions about fixing it—simply readjusting the value so

00:21:01.362 --> 00:21:06.482
that the polar circumference lined up perfectly with 40 million metres—but

00:21:06.862 --> 00:21:11.442
doing so would have rendered every existing metre stick obsolete.

00:21:12.152 --> 00:21:16.292
Redefining the metre in that way would have caused enormous disruption.

00:21:17.342 --> 00:21:21.199
Instead, the world decided to keep the metre as it was.

00:21:21.979 --> 00:21:27.049
After all, it was only a fraction of a millimetre off per metre, which

00:21:27.049 --> 00:21:31.069
was more than accurate enough for 18th-century practical purposes.

00:21:32.289 --> 00:21:37.079
Later refinements to the definition of the metre, like tying it to the speed of light,

00:21:37.589 --> 00:21:42.859
have made it infinitely more precise, but the original length is still the same.

00:21:44.029 --> 00:21:48.559
In other words, Méchain’s tiny error became enshrined in history.

00:21:49.269 --> 00:21:54.179
The Earth isn’t exactly 40 million metres in circumference, but

00:21:54.449 --> 00:21:58.179
the metric system has worked so well that it doesn’t really matter.

00:21:59.299 --> 00:22:02.739
It was a small price to pay for the simplicity and

00:22:02.739 --> 00:22:06.349
universality that the metric system brought to the world.

